
[1]prescribe

   PRESCRI'BE, v.t. [L. proescribo, to write before.]

   1. In medicine, to direct, as a remedy to be used or applied to a
   diseased patient. Be not offended with the physician who prescribes
   harsh remedies.

   2. To set or lay down authoritatively for direction; to give as a rule
   of conduct; as, to prescribe laws or rules.

   There's joy, when to wild will you laws prescribe.

   3. To direct.

   Let streams prescribe their fountains where to run.

    PRESCRI'BE, v.i. To write or give medical directions; to direct what
     remedies are to be used; as, to prescribe for a patient in a fever.

   1. To give law; to influence arbitrarily.

   A forwardness to prescribe to the opinions of others.

   2. In law, to claim by prescription; to claim a title to a thing by
   immemorial use and enjoyment; with for. A man may be allowed to
   prescribe for a right of way, a common or the like; a man cannot
   prescribe for a castle; he can prescribe only for incorporeal
   hereditaments.

   3. To influence by long use.
